Transmissible spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs)1 involve spongiform degeneration and astrocyte gliosis in the central nervous system leading to dementia and death (1). They can have genetic, sporadic, or infectious etiologies, exemplified by fatal familial insomnia, sporadic Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, and variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease in humans, respectively. They all involve the modification of prion precursor protein PrPc
